\b \cf0 \cb2 TECHNIQUE\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl320\ql\qnatural
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 \cb1 		PREVENTING APPLE BLOWOUTS\uc0\u8232 
\b0 While developing our recipe for baked apples, we couldn\'92t ignore a persistent problem: apples that \'93blew out\'94 and collapsed in the oven. Could removing the skin solve the issue? \uc0\u8232 \u8232 
\b EXPERIMENT
\b0 \uc0\u8232 We prepared two batches of six baked Granny Smith apples each, one skin-on, the other skin-off, using our placeholder filling and sauce (raisins, toasted pecans, and brown sugar for the filling; apple cider for the sauce). Then we baked each batch in a 13- by 9-inch baking dish in a 375-degree oven until the apples could be pierced easily with a knife. \u8232 \u8232 
\b RESULTS
\b0 \uc0\u8232 To our surprise, all the skin-off apples held their shape, without a single blowout. Within the skin-on batch, half of the apples collapsed. \u8232 \u8232 
\b EXPLANATION
\b0 \uc0\u8232 In nature, the peel protects an apple; in the oven, it traps moisture that\'92s been transformed into steam. As the steam attempts to escape, its outward pressure ruptures cells and eventually bursts through the apple\'92s skin, causing blowouts. Removing all the skin allows the steam to escape without damaging the fruit\'92s structure.\
